<HEADLINE> Iran Repatriates 136 Afghan Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Iran on Saturday repatriated 136
Afghan refugees to their homeland as part of an ongoing "voluntary
repatriation program," the Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
All the 136 refugees were repatriated from the central province
of Isfahan, from where some 9,586 Afghan have returned home since
the beginning of the current Iranian year on March 20.
</P>
<P>
The refugee repatriation program, which started on April 8, will
continue until October in line with an agreement signed between the
Iranian government and the Untied Nations High Commissioner for
Refugees (UNHCR).
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, some 100,000 Afghan refugees are to be
repatriated to Afghanistan in six months.
</P>
<P>
Toshiro Odahsima, head of the UNHCR office in Tehran, announced
on Tuesday that a total of 83,777 Afghan refugees have returned
home from different parts of Iran since the start of the program.
</P>
<P>
The UNHCR puts the total number of Afghan refugees in Iran at 1.
4 million, of which some 70,000 are living here illegally.
</P>
<P>
Afghan refugees have been blamed for the high rate of
unemployment in Iran. Labor Minister Hussein Kamali said in May
that about 2 million refugees, most of them Afghans, are working
illegally in Iran.
</P>
<P>
Last month, some 154 members of Iran's Majlis (parliament) also
urged President Mohammad Khatami's government to repatriate Afghan
refugees.
</P>
<P>
The increasing number of Afghan refugees and their long presence
here has given rise to numerous problems for Iranian citizens, the
Majlis members said in an open letter to the president. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
