<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Finance Ministers Call on OPEC to Increase Oil Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The finance ministers of the 15
European Union (EU) nations Saturday called on the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) to increase oil production.
</P>
<P>
In a communique issued after a meeting held in Versailles
southwest of Paris, EU finance ministers said that the present
price of oil makes up "a source of great concern."
</P>
<P>
"This should be dealt with, as OPEC has promised, by an
increase of production leading to a lower price," said the finance
ministers.
</P>
<P>
They called on OPEC to take measures to guarantee a market
supply which should be better adapted to the present world
economic situation.
</P>
<P>
The ministers also said that out of economic and environmental
reasons, the governments of the 15 EU countries will not cut oil
taxes to reduce oil price.
</P>
<P>
They also suggested that a coordination be launched in the
framework of the International Energy Agency on energy savings and
a policy of energy diversification.
</P>
<P>
OPEC countries will meet on Sunday in Vienna to discuss a
possible increase of oil production. 
</P>
</TEXT>
