<DOCNO> XIE20000909.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nearly 2,000 Contracts Shelved by U.S., Britain: Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The United States and British
delegates at the United Nations Sanctions Committee have put on
hold a total of 1,966 contracts Iraq signed with foreign countries
under the U.N. oil-for-food program, Iraqi Trade Ministry said on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In a statement carried by the official Iraqi News Agency, the
ministry said that the contracts, worth 3.3 billion U.S. dollars,
were meant for Iraq to import humanitarian supplies to alleviate
the crippling impacts of the decade-old sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The contracts, including 886 for the oil sector, 219 for health,
284 for electricity, 103 for transport and communication, were
concluded between Iraq and Arab, European and other countries.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that the U.S. and Britain block the contracts
to impede the implementation of the oil-for-food deal "to inflict
more harm on the Iraqi people."
</P>
<P>
The statement stressed that only the total lifting of the
sanctions can end Iraqi people's suffering.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad has frequently accused the U.S. and British members at
the U.N. Sanctions Committee of blocking its vital imports.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been under stringent U.N. sanctions ever since its 1990
invasion of Kuwait, but the U.N. oil-for-food accord started in
late 1996 allows it to export crude in return for U.N.-supervised
imports of food, medicine and other humanitarian goods.
</P>
<P>
Iraq says that the sanctions have claimed over 1.3 million
lives, causing a humanitarian crisis in the country.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions are not to be lifted until Iraq is given a clean
bill of health by the U.N. arms inspectors. But Iraq has barred U.
N. inspectors from entering since December 1998 when the U.S. and
Britain launched large-scale air strikes Baghdad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000909.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- The impact of the roaring oil prices on Turkey's
current account deficit is projected to amount to somewhere between
1.5 to 2 billion U.S. dollars by the end of the year, Turkish Daily
News reported on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that each one dollar increase in the prices of oil
per barrel means 180 million dollars on external accounts, assuming
that Turkey will import 180 million barrels of oil this year.
</P>
<P>
A leading culprit behind the deteriorating current account
balance, Turkey's oil import bill has grown by twice this year when
compared to 1998, which was also a year of economic growth.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of this year, Turkey imported 1.9 billion
dollars of crude oil compared to 1 billion in the same period of
1998.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- The Saudi Arab Monetary Association (SAMA) will start
to use the European single currency euro in all its monetary
accounts as of September 13, the Arabic-language daily Al-Alam Al-
Youm reported on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
SAMA has asked businessmen and financial institutions via the
Saudi Trade Chambers to stop issuing payment orders and documentary
credits in other European currencies as of September 13.
</P>
<P>
Saudi economists expect that Saudi Arabia and other Gulf
countries could adopt measures to reduce their national currencies'
linkage with the U.S. dollar and make a shift towards a broader
euro-dominated international currency basket, said the report.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkish brokerage firm Garanti Yatirim, U.S.
investment bank JP Morgan Capital and the National Bank of Greece
on Friday set up a special capital fund of 45 million U.S. dollars
to finance the development of small- and medium-sized enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The alliance has named the new entity Bosphorus Capital
Partners, which was created with equal contributions by the three
institutions.
</P>
<P>
The capital of the new company is expected shortly to increase
from 45 million dollars to 100 million dollars through
international funds.
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- The Central Bank of Iraq has announced that Iraqi
citizens living at home or abroad can open bank accounts in foreign
currency at the Iraqi banks in and outside Iraq.
</P>
<P>
However, the bank did not mention the interest rates on foreign
deposits.
</P>
<P>
Before the 1991 Gulf War, Iraqi dinar was officially traded at
3.2 U.S. dollars. Now, a dollar can buy about 2,000 Iraqi dinars,
said the bank in a circular.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey will set up a Highway Technology Transfer
Center in Ankara together with the U.S. Federal Highways
Administration.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Highway General Director Dincer Yigit said Friday that
they were ready to cooperate with any country on earthquakes-
resistant highway construction.
</P>
<P>
He added that they had already started cooperation with the
United States and Japan in this respect.
</P>
<P>
The center, which will be located on the Ankara-Istanbul
Highway, will enable Turkey to benefit from the U.S. experience in
highway construction and new technologies in this field, he said.
Other countries in the region will also benefit from this
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He noted that experts from the U.S. Federal Highways
Administration came to Turkey after last year's Marmara earthquake
and prepared a report on their findings regarding the situation of
Turkish highways.
</P>
<P>
They will hold a series of seminars on these results in Turkey
later this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
