<HEADLINE> Iraq Launches Anti-Measles Vaccination Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The Iraqi Health Ministry on
Saturday launched a six-day campaign to vaccinate Iraq's 900,000
children from nine months to five years old to contain measles.
</P>
<P>
The nationwide campaign aims at controlling infections and
mortality from measles among children, said Qussay Kamil, director
of the Health Education Department under the Health Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The ministry has made available all the necessary equipment,
including 5,000 vaccination teams, 750 trucks to transport the
teams and 1,000 health supervisors, Kamil said.
</P>
<P>
The campaign was conducted with the cooperation of the United
Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF) and the World Health Organization
(WHO).
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been struggling under the 10-year-old stringent U.N.
sanctions for its invasion of Kuwait in August 1990.
</P>
<P>
Beat Schweizer, head of the International Committee of the Red
Cross delegation in Iraq, has warned that Iraq's hospitals are
close to collapse.
</P>
<P>
Iraq claimed that more than 10,000 people, including 7,457
children, died in July as a direct result of malnutrition and
severe medicine shortage caused by the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
And this has brought the total number of victims of the
sanctions to 1,335,060 since 1990.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has repeatedly accused the U.S. and British members at the
U.N. Sanctions Committee of blocking the vital contracts Iraq
signed with foreign countries within the framework of the U.N. oil-
for-food program to import food, medicine and other basic goods.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. humanitarian program, which took effect in 1996, allows
Iraq to sell oil in return for humanitarian supplies under U.N.
supervision. 
</P>
</TEXT>
