<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean farm Workers Plan to Sue Government  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Secretary General of the Council Douglas Mutembwa told the
Zimbabwe News Agency that the government was neglecting its role
as the new employer on farms it was acquiring in the resettlement
program.
</P>
<P>
"The government must pay compensation to the farm workers or
give them retrenchment packages as their new employer," said
Mutembwa.
</P>
<P>
He said the organization was not against the land
redistribution process, but wanted the government to honor its
responsibility according to the Labor Relations Act.
</P>
<P>
He said they considered the action taken by the government to
ignore the farm workers as illegal retrenchment.
</P>
<P>
The Labor Relations Act stipulates that in case of a transfer
of ownership of an enterprise, the person who acquires the
enterprise becomes the new employer to the workers.
</P>
<P>
He said as the new employer, the government should comply with
contractual agreements made between the former employers and the
employees.
</P>
<P>
vice-president Joseph Msika's secretary Frederick Chunga told
the national news agency that the government had put in place
policies to cater for farm workers.
</P>
<P>
Mutembwa said,"People can come up with policies, but the fact
remains that the white farms' workers are suffering. The
government is resettling people while it is displacing others."
</P>
<P>
More than 240,000 white farms' workers are estimated to lose
employment because of the fast track land reform program expected
to finish before the rain season starts at the end of next month.
</P>
<P>
The government has embarked on the land reform process to
correct the historical imbalance in which only 4,500 white farmers
own more than 70 percent of arable land with the majority of the
12.5 million people squashed on unproductive land. 
</P>
</TEXT>
