<HEADLINE> Ethiopia, Italy Discuss Return of Axum Obelisk  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Walta Information Center of Ethiopia reported Saturday that in
a meeting held recently in Axum town, about 600 km north of Addis
Ababa, the Italian team proposed that the obelisk should be cut
into three pieces for the convenience of transportation.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian side have consented to the proposal, said Jara
Hailemariam, head of the Ethiopian Heritage Research and
Protection Organization.
</P>
<P>
The 28-meter-high Axum obelisk, one of the most famous
Ethiopian historical relics, was looted by Italian troops during
their occupation of Ethiopia between 1936 and 1941.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that experts of the two countries had also
discussed the availability of transport infrastructure and the
mode of transportation, as well as the provision of other
machinery for the safe handling of the obelisk, and have agreed
that these facilities could be provided by the Ethiopian side,
Jara said.
</P>
<P>
However, Jara noted that the two sides had not decided when the
whole process should be started. Further consultations are to be
conducted in Addis Ababa, he said. 
</P>
