<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Ministers Urge More Oil Production to Reduce Price </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 9 (Xinhua) -- European Union finance
ministers on Saturday urged the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries (OPEC) to increase oil production so as to
reduce prices.
</P>
<P>
The ministers said in a joint statement available here that
they considered the current level of oil prices was a source of
major concern and that the rise in oil prices had to be dealt with
as the OPEC has promised by increased production leading to a
lower price.
</P>
<P>
"Oil prices need to return to a level that preserves worldwide
growth," the ministers said in their statement issued after their
meeting at Versailles.
</P>
<P>
The EU finance ministers did not say what oil price they wanted.
</P>
<P>
The finance ministers, however, said that their governments
would not change their policy on oil taxation for economic and
environmental reasons.
</P>
<P>
The rising oil prices and hence fuel prices have led to public
unrest in several EU countries. Truck drivers in France set up
road blockades to protest against the rising fuel prices. They
were later joined by farmers and taxi drivers.
</P>
<P>
Across the border in Germany and across the channel in Britain,
truck drivers also took to the streets and blocked fuel depots to
protest.
</P>
<P>
The Belgian truck drivers' union is organizing a downtown
driving demonstration in the capital city of Brussels on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The French authorities have earlier moved to cut down the
taxation on fuels to calm the protesters, yet the latter would
like to pressure for more cuts on fuel taxes.
</P>
<P>
The rocketing of oil prices posted since early 1999 has
triggered a debate in the EU on the crude oil prices, refining and
distribution as well as taxation on oil products, the three
components of fuel prices.
</P>
<P>
The EU officials would hold the tight production quota by the
OPEC responsible for the rising crude oil prices that in turn had
lead to rising fuel prices.
</P>
<P>
Crude oil prices now seem determined to fluctuate within a band
of 30 U.S. dollars a barrel and it entered that band in February
this year following an uninterrupted rise since December 1998 when
the crude oil price bottomed out at 10 dollars a barrel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
