<DOCNO> XIE20000909.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Seeks Long-Term Solutions vs. Peso Speculation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government is
now drawing up long-term measures that would involve the banking
sector and the public to further strengthen the peso against
speculative trading.
</P>
<P>
Executive Secretary Ronaldo Zamora disclosed this plan Saturday
as he called on banks not to sell too much U.S. dollars to
multinational corporations which, he said, can eat up as much as
three months' supply of dollars in one transaction, the
Philippines News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"The Central Bank of the Philippines can do that but the other
banks must also play a role," Zamora said, referring to the fight
against speculators.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, the central bank finally turned to its dollar
reserves to intervene in the market to prop up the peso, improving
its standing from P45.90 to P45.50 to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
But Zamora said the government cannot continue dipping into its
dollar reserves to ward off speculative trading and must come up
with a long-term program to discourage this practice.
</P>
<P>
The government has over 15 billion dollars in gross
international reserves, the highest in the country's financial
history.
</P>
<P>
"Those speculative ventures against the peso must be stopped,"
Zamora said.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, he said the government is careful to make sure
that its intervention to prop up the peso's value would not
distort market operations.
</P>
<P>
He said last week's intervention should be a signal that while
the economy remains market-driven, the government will not allow
speculators to pull down the peso's value artificially.
</P>
<P>
Zamora assured the public that the central bank continues to
maintain a delicate balance in its intervention in the market to
defend the peso. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000909.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Foreign Currency Assets Jump Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The fall in India's foreign
currency assets (FCA) has finally been arrested after more than
eight weeks of continuous decline, with the assets rising by 111
million U.S. dollars to 32.787 billion dollars during the week
ended September 1, the Press Trust of India (PTI) reported on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In tandem with the increase in the FCA, the country's foreign
currency reserves also inched up by 17 million dollars to 35.619
billion U.S. dollars, the PTI quoted the Reserve Bank of India in
Mumbai as saying in its weekly statistical supplement.
</P>
<P>
While the special drawing rights remained static at two million
dollars, gold reserves were down by 94 million dollars to 190
million dollars, the supplement added.
</P>
<P>
India's foreign currency reserves had kept on falling almost
throughout August as the country's currency rupees depreciated
sharply against U.S. dollar, leading to a strong dollar demand in
the foreign exchange market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
