<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1530 GMT, September 9 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The three-day U.N. Millennium Summit
concluded on Friday evening at the U.N. headquarters in New York
with the adoption of a declaration.
</P>
<P>
The summit, co-chaired by President of Namibia Sam Nujoma,
whose country held the presidency of the 54th session of the
United Nations General Assembly, and President of Finland Tarja
Halone, whose country holds the presidency of the 55th session of
the General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
The summit, under the official theme "The United Nations in the
21st Century," attracted more than 160 heads of state or
government, the largest-ever gathering of the world's leaders in U.
N. history. (U.N.-Millennium Summit-Declaration)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW - A Russian diplomat involved in a recent scandal of
alleged spying activities in Japan has flown home, the Interfax
news agency reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
It was not clear whether military attache of the Russian
Embassy Andrei Bogatenkov left Japan voluntarily or was expelled
by Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, the Japanese police arrested Shigehiro Hagisaki, a
38-year-old retired naval officer currently working for the
national institute of defense research, on suspicion of selling
classified information to Russian intelligence, Russian media
reported. (Russia-Japan-Diplomat Scandal)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI -- The famine situation in Kenya is still severe and
persistent with at least 3.3 million people being directly
affected, the People daily reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted Kenya's National Drought Response
Committee Chairman Uhuru Kenyatta as saying at the closure of a
drought preparedness intervention and recovery program that the
number of people succumbing to hunger continues to rise,
especially in the pastoral and marginal districts.
</P>
<P>
Kenya is experiencing the worst drought over the past 40 years,
resulting in food shortage after crop failure for three successive
harvesting seasons, power rationing nationwide and water rationing
in cities. (Kenya-Famine)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- France's largest national truckers' union Saturday
agreed to lift its blockade on oil refineries and storehouses to
end a week-long crisis of oil supply in the country.
</P>
<P>
Daniel Chevallier, president of the National Union of
Syndicated Organizations of Road Haulers, said at a press
conference that Minister of Transport Jean-Claude Gayssot has
agreed to help those trucking companies with most difficulties.
</P>
<P>
Two other national truckers' unions have also agreed to lift
the blockade, which has caused a nationwide shortage of oil supply.
(France-Blockade-Lifting)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin on Saturday hailed
the release of French hostage Stephane Loisy by the Philippine
Muslim rebel group Abu Sayyaf.
</P>
<P>
The French Foreign Ministry said France is making efforts to
seek the release of two other French hostages -- two journalists
working for France 2 TV channel Jean-Jacques Le Garrec and Roland
Madura -- who are still held by the rebels of Abu Sayyaf in the
southern Philippine island of Jolo. (France-Hostage-Release)
</P>
</TEXT>
