<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Women Runner Promises Gold Medal in Sydney </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 9 (Xinhua) -- World junior cross-country
champion, Kenya's women runner Vivian Cheruiyot, looks forward to
winning a gold medal at the Olympic Games in Sydney, Australia,
next week.
</P>
<P>
Cheruiyot who will feature in the 5,000 meters is among several
top runners who chose to train in the country instead of Adelaide,
Australia, local media reproted.
</P>
<P>
"I'm fully prepared and winning has become my way of life. I'm
going for gold medal," she said at the office of the National
Olympic Committee of Kenya in the capital Nairobi on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Cheruiyot has finalized her travel arrangements in readiness
for departure to Sydney next Monday.
</P>
<P>
The 16-year-old Cheruiyot confirmed her place in the Kenya
Olympic team this week after qualifying during an international
meeting in Viareggio, Italy, on Agust 22. She clocked 15 minutes
16.10 seconds.
</P>
<P>
The youthful star came into the national limelight after
winning a silver medal in Belfast, Britain, in 1998 and won a
bronze in 5,000 meters in last year's All Africa Games in South
Africa.
</P>
<P>
Kenya is expected to do well in middle and long distance races
in Sydney and the country is also represented in women's
volleyball, cycling, boxing, swimming and archery. 
</P>
</TEXT>
