<HEADLINE> Spadea Replaces Agassi on U.S. Olympic Tennis Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Vince Spadea was placed on
the U.S. Olympic tennis team Saturday, succeeding Andre Agassi,
despite winning just two matches all year and holding a 119 world
ranking.
</P>
<P>
Agassi withdrew from the team earlier this week after revealing
his mother and sister are battling breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
Spadea completes the U.S. team which includes Todd Martin,
Michael Chang and Jeff Tarango. Alex O'Brien and Jared Palmer will
represent the United States in doubles.
</P>
<P>
Spadea, a quarterfinalist in the 1999 Australian Open, was
ranked a career-best 19th a year ago. He lost his first 17 matches
this year before ending the losing streak with a first-round
victory over Greg Rusedski at Wimbledon. His other victory came
the next week when he defeated Sergi Brugera at Gstaad.
</P>
<P>
Spadea, 26, played for the U.S. Davis Cup team in July, losing
to Juan Carlos Ferrero as Spain blanked the United States 5-0.
</P>
<P>
The tennis competition at the Olympics starts Sept. 19.
</P>
</TEXT>
