<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yak Research Draws World Attention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Research on yaks and plateau
environment by Chinese scientists has drawn world attention.
</P>
<P>
More than 70 scholars from 17 countries and international
organizations participated in the third International Symposium on
Yaks, which concluded today in Lhasa, capital of the Tibet
Autonomous Region in southwest China.
</P>
<P>
Yaks live on high and cold plateaus, and provide a source of
meat, dairy and woolen products. China has over 12 million yaks,
or 85 percent of yaks found in the world.
</P>
<P>
The research on the animal started in China in the 1970s,
concentrated in Qinghai, Tibet, Sichuan, Gansu and Xinjiang, the
major production areas of yaks.
</P>
<P>
Chinese scientists have extracted photosensitive material from
the bone of yaks. And a kind of enzyme took from yak blood can be
used to make high-quality cosmetics and food additives.
</P>
<P>
Chinese researchers also found that the meat of yak has high
content of protein and is low in fat.
</P>
<P>
Denis Hoffmann, a representative from the United Nations Food
and Agricultural Organization, said China's research on yaks will
be helpful to study about disease prevention in the animal
husbandry, grassland development, protection of genetic resources
and eco-system.
</P>
<P>
There are over 20 enterprises in Tibet dealing in yak products
from meat and fur processing to yak horn handicrafts.
</P>
<P>
The symposium has strengthened yak research and industry
development, experts say.  
</P>
</TEXT>
