<HEADLINE> France Hails Release of Hostage by Philippine Muslim Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 9 (Xinhua) -- French Prime Minister Lionel
Jospin on Saturday hailed the release of French hostage Stephane
Loisy by the Philippine Muslim rebel group Abu Sayyaf.
</P>
<P>
"This happy news marks the end of his ordeal that undergone
with courage and dignity on the part of his parents and brother,"
said Jospin.
</P>
<P>
The French Foreign Ministry said France is making efforts to
seek the release of two other French hostages -- two journalists
working for France 2 TV channel Jean-Jacques Le Garrec and Roland
Madura -- who are still held by the rebels of Abu Sayyaf in the
southern Philippine island of Jolo.
</P>
<P>
French President Jacques Chirac Saturday called the families of
the two journalists, expressing his determination to seek their
release in a safe and sound condition.
</P>
<P>
A Libyan mediator in the hostage crisis said on the same day
that the rebels will release the two journalists within 24 hours,
Agence France-Presse (AFP) reported.
</P>
<P>
AFP quoted the Gaddafi Foundation in Tripoli as saying that a
Libyan plane will fly to the Philippines on Saturday to bring four
newly released hostages, including Stephane Loisy, to Tripoli.
</P>
</TEXT>
