<HEADLINE> Richardson Pulls out of Sydney Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SYDNEY, September 9 (Xinhua) -- British 400m runner Mark
Richardson is out of the Olympic Games, the International Amateur
Athletic Federation confirmed on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
IAAF media director Giorgio Reineri revealed it had been agreed
between the lawyers of both camps that Richardson's case should be
delayed until after the Games.
</P>
<P>
The 27-year-old runner tested positive for the banned steroid
nandrolone in October 1999 but was cleared of any wrong-doing by
UK Athletics in July.
</P>
<P>
However the IAAF ordered Richardson's case appear before their
Court of Arbitration - initially announcing it would be presided
on before the Olympics began on September 15.
</P>
<P>
But both parties require more time to get their documentation
prepared in the proper manner, meaning Richardson will miss the
Games.
</P>
<P>
A statement from the IAAF said: "A request from UK Athletics to
adjourn the arbitration hearing of the British 400m runner Mark
Richardson has been accepted.
</P>
<P>
"The IAAF raised no objection to the request from UK Athletics
and noted that Mark Richardson will not compete in the 2000
Olympic Games." 
</P>
</TEXT>
