<DOCNO> XIE20000909.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2nd lead: Four Remaining Sipadan European Hostages Freed EDS Update With Details, Background </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The freed four European
hostages arrived in the southern city of Zamboanga Saturday
afternoon after more than four months of ordeal in the Abu Sayyaf'
s jungle lair in nearby Jolo island, Sulu province.
</P>
<P>
They arrived by helicopter at the Edwin Andrews air base in
Zamboanga at around 5:30 p.m., under the escort of Philippine
government chief negotiator Robert Aventajao, Libyan envoy Rajab
Azzarouq and Sulu governor Abdusakur Tan, the ABS-CBN TV station
reported.
</P>
<P>
At the air base, Aventajado formally turned over the four --
two Finns, one French and one German -- to the ambassadors of
their countries.
</P>
<P>
The four were among the original group of 21 hostages seized by
the Abu Sayyaf on Malaysia's resort island of Sipadan on April 23
and later brought to Jolo.
</P>
<P>
An excited German Marc Wallert, whose parents were released
separately earlier, expressed his thanks for everyone who cares
about them, saying he couldn't describe his feeling at the moment.
</P>
<P>
One of the Finns, Risto Mirco Vahanen, said he would "kiss the
earth of Finland."
</P>
<P>
Calling "a nightmare" their near 140 days of captivity in the
rebels' jungle lair in Jolo, he extended his sincere thanks to
Aventajado and Azzarouq and all those who worked hard to " safely
bring us out of terror."
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference held later at the air base,
Aventajado said Saturday is a happy day, but "let's not forget the
mission is not over and there are still two French journalists not
released."
</P>
<P>
The two French journalists were abducted by the Abu Sayyaf in
Jolo in July while covering the hostage crisis.
</P>
<P>
Azzarouq, on his part, said they would continue to work for the
release of the two French journalists and one Filipino, the last
remaining hostage of the Sipadan group still in the hands of the
Abu Sayyaf rebels.
</P>
<P>
The Finnish, French and German ambassadors expressed their
gratitude to the Philippine government and Aventajado and Azzarouq
for their efforts in securing the safe release of the hostages.
</P>
<P>
They also thanked for Libyan involvement in solving the hostage
crisis.
</P>
<P>
The four Europeans were later flown to the central city of Cebu
where a chartered Libyan plane will reportedly fly them to the
Libyan capital of Tripoli Sunday.
</P>
<P>
It has been widely reported that Libya had agreed to pay 1
million U.S. dollars each for the six foreign hostages in addition
to an earlier offer of 25 million dollars in ransom to the Abu
Sayyaf for the release of their hostages.
</P>
<P>
But both Tripoli and Manila have denied that they paid any
ransoms. Libyan said its funds were for livelihood projects for
Muslim areas in Mindanao in the southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said factional fighting in the Abu Sayyaf broke
out Saturday morning in Jolo, raising fears that the Europeans'
release would be delayed again after the rebel group postponed its
promised release of six European hostages on Friday for reported
disagreement over ransom.
</P>
<P>
Fighting broke out around 10 a.m. between one faction of the
Abu Sayyaf led by Ghlib Andang, better known as Commander Robot,
and Mujib Susukan and another faction led by Abu Sabar and a
certain Commander Randy over whether to release four or all the
six European hostages held by the Abu Sayyaf.
</P>
<P>
The faction of Commander Robot reportedly wanted to free only
the remaining four Sipandan hostages it held while the faction of
Abu Sabar wanted its two captives, the two French journalists
abducted in Jolo in July, released together with the four Sipadan
hostages.
</P>
<P>
A team of government emissaries going to Jolo to secure the
release of the hostages was caught in the cross-fire between two
factions of the Abu Sayyaf in Talipao town, Jolo, which killed one
bodyguard of the negotiating team and wounded five others.
</P>
</TEXT>
