<DOCNO> XIE20000909.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Famine Situation in Kenya Still Bad: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The famine situation in Kenya
is still severe and persistent with at least 3.3 million people
being directly affected, the People daily reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted Kenya's National Drought Response
Committee Chairman Uhuru Kenyatta as saying at the closure of a
drought preparedness intervention and recovery program that the
number of people succumbing to hunger continues to rise,
especially in the pastoral and marginal districts.
</P>
<P>
Kenya is experiencing the worst drought over the past 40 years,
resulting in food shortage after crop failure for three successive
harvesting seasons, power rationing nationwide and water rationing
in cities.
</P>
<P>
The stocks in the national food reserve are declining at a
worrying rate, Kenyatta said.
</P>
<P>
He warned that the nutritional status of most of the population
in the country, particularly children and women, has worsened,
thus making them vulnerable to diseases.
</P>
<P>
Uhuru appealed for more food aid, saying the situation is yet
to be brought to manageable levels and the current food shortage
has pushed prices beyond the reach of susceptible groups. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
