<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jayasinghe and Thompson enjoy double sprint victories </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's sprint queen
Susanthika Jayasinghe and Obadele Thompson of Barbados enjoyed a
spring double at the Super Meet 2000 athletics event in Yokohama
on Saturday to tune up for the Sydney Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Tatiana Lebedeva and Koji Murofushi issued an
Olympic warning with the Russian triple jumper setting the second
best mark in history and the Japanese setting a new national mark
of 81.08 meters to win the hammer throw.
</P>
<P>
Lebedeva, who had held the best mark of the season with 15.01
meters, set a new Russian national record with a mark of 15.32m to
edge Americans Tiombe Hurd and Sheila Hudson. Inessa kravets of
the Ukraine holds the current world record of 15.50m.
</P>
<P>
Susanthika, the 1997 world silver medallist, bettered her
personal best by one hundredth of a second to win the women's 200
metres in 22.32, and then timed 11.04 to win the 100m.
</P>
<P>
Thompson also set a new personal best and a meet record by
clocking 19.97 to win the men's 200m. His winning time in the 100m
was 10.12.
</P>
<P>
China's Yu Juan won the women's shot put with 17.19 meters, the
second and third places went to two Japanese athletes.
</P>
<P>
Pole vault's greatest ever exponent Sergei Bubuka of the
Ukraine, who set a world record twice in this meet in the past,
bid a sad farewell to his fans in Japan as he left the stadium
without a record. South African Okkert Brits cleared 5.70 meters
for the champion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
