<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Diplomat in Japan Spy Scandal Returns Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 9 (Xinhua) - A Russian diplomat involved in a
recent scandal of alleged spying activities in Japan has flown
home, the Interfax news agency reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
It was not clear whether military attache of the Russian
Embassy Andrei Bogatenkov left Japan voluntarily or was expelled
by Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, the Japanese police arrested Shigehiro Hagisaki, a
38-year-old retired naval officer currently working for the
national institute of defense research, on suspicion of selling
classified information to Russian intelligence, Russian media
reported.
</P>
<P>
Moscow has yet to decide whether to deport a Japanese diplomat
in retaliation, Interfax quoted Russian Deputy Foreign Minister
Alexander Losyukov as saying.
</P>
<P>
Russia "must act very carefully here, look into all
circumstances and make a balanced decision with the context of
Russian-Japanese relations taken into account among other things,"
Losyukov said.
</P>
<P>
The term of Bogatenkov's mission "has nearly expired and he was
about to leave Japan regardless of the scandal," the deputy
foreign minister said.
</P>
<P>
The arrest took place in a Tokyo restaurant where Hagisaki met
with Bogatenkov to whom, according to Japanese police, the naval
officer had been handing over classified information for a long
time.
</P>
<P>
The previous similar incident in relations between Moscow and
Tokyo took place 20 years ago, Interfax said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
