<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1stlead: Four Remaining Sipadan European Hostages Freed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The Abu Sayyaf freed Saturday
afternoon the four remaining European hostages it kidnapped from
Malaysia in April, the local ABS-CBN TV station reported.
</P>
<P>
The government has sent a helicopter to the southern island of
Jolo from nearby Zamboanga city to fetch the four Europeans, it
said.
</P>
<P>
The four -- two Finns, one French and one German, were among
the original group of 21 hostages seized by the Abu Sayyaf on
Malaysia's resort island of Sipadan on April 23 and later brought
to Jolo, Sulu province.
</P>
<P>
Finnish, French and German ambassadors to the Philippines are
reportedly now in Zamboanga waiting for the arrival of their
countrymen.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said factional fighting in the Abu Sayyaf broke
out Saturday morning in Jolo, raising fears that their release
would be delayed again after the rebel group postponed its
promised release of six European hostages on Friday for reported
disagreement over ransom.
</P>
<P>
A team of government negotiators going to Jolo to secure the
release of the hostages was caught in the cross-fire between two
factions of the Abu Sayyaf in Talipao town, Jolo, which killed one
bodyguard of the negotiating team and wounded five others, the ABS-
CBN said.
</P>
<P>
Fighting broke out around 10 a.m. between one faction of the
Abu Sayyaf led by Ghlib Andang, better known as Commander Robot,
and Mujib Susukan and another faction led by Abu Sabar and a
certain Commander Randy over whether to release four or all the
six European hostages held by the Abu Sayyaf for months in its
jungle lairs in Jolo.
</P>
<P>
The faction of Commander Rbot reportedly wanted to free only
the remaining four Sipandan hostages it held while the faction of
Abu Sabar wanted its two captives, the two French journalists
abducted in Jolo in July, released together with the four Sipadan
hostages.
</P>
<P>
So far, the Abu Sayyaf is still holding one Filipino, the last
of the Sipandan hostages, the two French journalists and 12
Christian evangelists who went to the rebel camps in July to pray
for the hostages. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
