<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwanda Plans Railway to Link Indian Ocean via Tanzanian Port </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Rwanda is planning to
construct a railway to link its capital Kigali to the Isaka dry
port in western Tanzania to facilitate transportation from the
lank-locked country to the Indian Ocean.
</P>
<P>
According to Rwandan Ambassador to Tanzania Zephyr Mutanguha,
his government is trying hard to convince donor countries to fund
the project.
</P>
<P>
He described the inauguration of the Isaka dry port in
Shinyanga Region Thursday as a major step forward for the economic
development in Rwanda, media here reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"To enable the port to be of immense help to the common man in
Rwanda we are planning the railway line so as to reduce freight
costs," he said.
</P>
<P>
He urged the Tanzania Railway Corporation and the Tanzania
Revenue Authority to ensure speedy, reliable and timely ferrying
of cargoes going through this port.
</P>
<P>
With a capacity of handling 42,000 tons of break-bulk cargo and
13,000 twenty-foot containers annually, the Isaka port will be
able to effectively handle goods bound to and from Rwanda and two
other landlocked countries, Burundi and the Democratic Republic of
the Congo.
</P>
<P>
The three countries' sea-borne goods transportation via the
Isaka dry port via Tanzania's Central Railway to Dar es Salaam is
502 kilometers shorter than the existing northern corridor that
runs to Kenya's Indian coast city of Mombassa.
</P>
<P>
Cargo-handling time is expected to be reduced from the current
over 14 days to about five days and transportation costs by 40
percent, Tanzanian officials said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
