<DOCNO> XIE20000909.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Voronin Warms Up for Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
TOKYO, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Russian high jumper Vyacheslav
Voronin defeated some of his top rivals at the eve of the Sydney
Olympic Games when he won the Super Meet 2000 men's high jump
event with 2.33 meters in Yokohama, Japan on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Voronin, the reigning world champion, beat Cuban world record
holder Javier Sotomayor at 2.28 meters and 1996 Atlanta gold medal
winner American Charles Austin at 2.31 meters in the final
athletics match before the Sydney Olympics.
</P>
<P>
Voronin failed on his first two attempts at 2.33 meters but
soared over the bar on his third attempt and managed to safely
land on the crash mat's edge by a matter of centimeters.
</P>
<P>
"I am honored with my result today but I think at the Olympics,
I don't know what can happen," Voronin said.
</P>
<P>
Sotomayor, battling injuries after recently being reinstated
following a drug suspension, had two dismal attempts at 2.33
meters before scraping the bar on his third failed attempt.
</P>
<P>
"This year I am not aiming for a new world record because I
have been away for quite a long time. I hope to aim for 2.36 meter-
jump at Sydney," Sotomayor said, adding that he feels he is in
good shape going into Sydney.
</P>
<P>
Britain's Jonathan Edwards won the triple jump with a mark of
17.32 meters. Fellow Briton Larry Achike was a distant second at
16.56 meters and Chinese Gu Junjie third at 16.37. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
