<DOCNO> XIE20000909.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Carrard: Doping Report Based on Old Information </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
SYDNEY, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Francois Carrard, director-
general of the International Olympic Committee (IOC) said on
Saturday that a U.S.report criticising the organisation's record
on doping was out of date because it was based on a four-year-old
study.
</P>
<P>
The report, due to be released on Sunday, was leaked to New
York Times along with critical comments from the director of the U.
S. Office of National Drug Control Policy, Barry McCaffrey.
</P>
<P>
"When the Games begin millions of children will watch every
event," McCaffrey was quoted as saying. "Unless we continue to rid
the Games of doping and drugs, these children will also take the
same drugs as they see their stars cheating with."
</P>
<P>
Carrard told a news conference on Saturday that although he
had not yet read the report he had been informed it was based on
research carried out in 1996 and might not reflect what was being
done now.
</P>
<P>
"I am absolutely convinced that the IOC, the international
federations and the NOC's (National Olympic Committees) are doing
the utmost and the most serious efforts to complete that fight,
and it is a most serious fight," he said. "We will see what
happens in Sydney." 
</P>
