<HEADLINE> Kenya to Complete First Phase of Retrenchment Next Friday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government's first
phase of civil service retrenchment involving 25,780 civil
servants from 16 ministries including the Office of the President
will be completed by next Friday, Kenyan press reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In total, 48,829 civil servants will have been retrenched by
June 2002 in order to create a leaner, more shipshape and
productive civil service, said Kenyan Cabinet Minister William ole
Ntimama on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Kenya now has a total of over 215,000 civil servants.
</P>
<P>
"The government expenditure must be restrained in order to free-
up capital for private sector investment that will create new
employment," Ntimama said.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, each retrenched will receive a
severance payment of 40,000 shillings (about 520 U.S. dollars)
which the government could afford, plus their lump-sum pension and
a monthly pension for life.
</P>
<P>
The government will organize training for all the retirees to
prepare them psychologically and equip them with basic knowledge
and skills to enable them to utilize their retirement benefits, he
explained, saying that the training of the retrenched will kick
off from next Monday at 200 centers nationwide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
