<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Appeals for Release of Suspended Assistance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia has called on
the international financial institutions to release more than 1
billion U.S. dollars which were promised as development assistance
before the war between Ethiopia and Eritrea broke out in May 1998.
</P>
<P>
The aid was suspended during the Ethio-Eritrean border conflict,
but the two countries already signed a ceasefire agreement in June
this year, Ethiopia's Ministry of Economic Development and
Cooperation said in a statement Friday.
</P>
<P>
"The aid suspension vastly affected projects such as food
security, education and road construction which had been supported
by the donor community as priority areas for poverty alleviation,"
said Gezazhew Bizuayehu, a ranking official with the ministry.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the average foreign development aid that the sub-
Saharan African countries receive is between 30 and 40 U.S.
dollars per capita, Bizuayehu complained that foreign aid to
Ethiopia has fallen from 12 U.S. dollars per capita before its war
with Eritrea broke out to eight U.S. dollars per person..
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia gets development assistance mainly from the
International Monetary Fund, the World Bank, the European Union
and western countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
