<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, September 9 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- The United Nations High Commissioner for
Refugees (UNHCR) said on Friday that its activities had come to an
end in relation to the voluntary return of the Guatemalans and
related programs.
</P>
<P>
The UNHCR said in a communique that all its programs during the
last nine years were carried out in coordination with the
Guatemalan government and other international organizations.
During a ceremony to officially declare the end of the UNHCR
programs, a UNHCR official said several programs had been
implemented to help refugees who had returned to Guatemala. These
programs started with negotiations on a voluntary repatriation of
some 8,000 families, or 43,000 people. (Guatemala-UNHCR-Completion)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- South Korea and the United States Forces Korea (USFK)
are discussing how to designate a part of Demilitarized Zone (DMZ)
for an inter-Korean area that Seoul and Pyongyang can jointly
manage, the Defense Ministry said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The area is needed for reconstruction of the railway line from
Seoul to Shinuiju in the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (
DPRK) and a parallel road. The entire DMZ is wholly under the
control of the USFK in accordance with the 1953 armistice
agreement. (SKorea-USFK)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The United Nations Security Council on Friday
urged the government of Indonesia to immediately disarm and
disband the militiamen in West Timor of Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
In its resolution which was unanimously adopted, the 15-member
security council also called on Indonesia to restore law and
ensure safety and security in the refugee camps and for
humanitarian workers in West Timor, and to prevent cross-border
incursions by the militia into East Timor. A group of militiamen
against the independence of East Timor on Wednesday stormed the
local office of the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugee (
UNHCR) in West Timor and killed three UNHCR workers. (UN-Indonesia-
Timor)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
VIENNA -- The panel of outside experts appointed by the
European Union (EU) suggested on Friday that the seven-month-old
political sanctions imposed by the EU against the Austrian
government for allowing the ultra-right Freedom Party into the
coalition government be lifted.
</P>
<P>
"The Austrian government's respect in particular for the rights
of minorities, refugees and immigrants is not inferior to that of
the other European Union member states," the panel said in a
report submitted to French President Jacques Chirac, whose country
currently holds the rotating EU presidency. "In some areas,
particularly concerning the rights of national minorities,
Austrian standards can be considered to be higher than those
applied in many other EU countries," it said. (EU-Austria-
Sanctions) 
