<HEADLINE> Hickman to Concentrate on 100 Meters Butterfly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
SYDNEY, September 9 (Xinhua) -- British swimmer James Hickman
has decided to withdraw from the Olympic 200 meters individual
medley event so as to focus on the 100m butterfly.
</P>
<P>
The British team said that the 24-year-old had decided to
restrict himself to three events at the Games -- the 100 and 200
meters butterfly and the 4x100 meters medley relay.
</P>
<P>
According to the schedule, the 100 meters butterfly semifinal
is on the same night as the 200 meters individual medley final and
Hickman believes he has a far greater chance to win in the
butterfly event.
</P>
<P>
He took a silver medal in the 200 meter butterfly and a bronze
in the 100 butterfly at July's European championships in Helsinki.
He was last in the 200 individual medley final.
</P>
<P>
Hickman, a 200 meters individual medley finalist at the 1998
world championships, will not be replaced in the event as he was
the only Briton to achieve the qualifying standard. 
