<HEADLINE> Kodak, Sharp to Jointly Manufacture Digital Camera </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 8 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Eastman Kodak Co. and
Japan's Sharp Corp. have agreed to jointly manufacture digital
cameras, said Kodak Friday in a news release.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Sharp will be the original equipment
manufacturer in Japan for "lower-end" cameras to be sold in the
United States under the Kodak brand name. Terms of the agreement,
however, were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
"We are seeking expansion of the (digital camera) line into
lower-end cameras," priced under 200 U.S. dollars, said Kodak
spokesman Paul Allen.
</P>
<P>
Kodak's new line of digital cameras will be used largely for
sending digital images via electronic mail or for posting on Web
pages, Allen said. Previously Kodak had focused on pricier, high-
resolution, mega-pixel digital cameras for high-quality prints.
</P>
<P>
Both companies said they would seek to expand the alliance into
new products in the future. Analysts noted that the deal is the
first of its kind for Kodak and Sharp.  
</P>
