<HEADLINE> Myanmar Calls for Strengthening of U.N. in New Millennium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar has called for
strengthening of the U.N. organization while entering the new
millennium, saying that by doing so it will be able to cope with
new challenges and new realities.
</P>
<P>
In his statement given at the Millennium Summit in New York on
Thursday, Myanmar Foreign Minister U Win Aung stressed the
paramount importance of the role played by the U.N., calling for
reform of the organization without weakening the principles and
charters of the organization.
</P>
<P>
The cardinal principles of sovereignty, territorial integrity,
sovereign equality and non-interference in the internal affairs
have enabled the world community to live in peace with one another,
he pointed out, disagreeing with those who contend that these
principles are outdated and that it does not need them in the new
century.
</P>
<P>
He hoped the summit would once again reaffirm the cardinal
principles of international conduct, saying that these principles
have served well in the old millennium and will serve equally in
the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that there is no single formula that could be
applied to all countries, warning that there would be a mistake
for powerful countries to impose their systems on others and mold
the developing countries in their own image.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that Myanmar is building a genuine and durable
democratic system in its own way, saying that in Myanmar "the
flames of conflicts have been extinguished, the guns have been
silenced."
</P>
<P>
He charged the opposition forces in the country with embarking
on a path of destruction and confrontation, warning that these
acts could only impede the process of democratization of the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
