<HEADLINE> EU Panel Suggests Ending Sanctions Against Austria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, September 8 (Xinhua) - The panel of outside experts
appointed by the European Union (EU) suggested on Friday that the
seven-month-old political sanctions imposed by the EU against the
Austrian government for allowing the ultra-right Freedom Party
into the coalition government be lifted.
</P>
<P>
"The Austrian government's respect in particular for the rights
of minorities, refugees and immigrants is not inferior to that of
the other European Union member states," the panel said in a
report submitted to French President Jacques Chirac, whose country
currently holds the rotating EU presidency.
</P>
<P>
"In some areas, particularly concerning the rights of national
minorities, Austrian standards can be considered to be higher than
those applied in many other EU countries," it said.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, it added, it is still correct to describe the
Freedom Party, which entered the government in February, as an
ultra-right party "with radical elements."
</P>
<P>
It said the sanctions had been effective in upholding European
values, but they should end now.
</P>
<P>
It explained that the sanctions had incited nationalism in
Austria, and was misunderstood as a punishment against Austrians.
</P>
<P>
The panel's report received widespread welcome in Austria.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions, imposed by the EU on February 3, bar high-level
bilateral contacts with Austrian Chancellor Wolfgang Schuessel's
government. In accordance with the sanctions announced by Portugal
on behalf of the EU, all bilateral meetings with the Austrian
government are to be suspended and any Austria-proposed candidate
seeking positions in international organizations will not be
supported. 
</P>
