<HEADLINE> Russia, Kyrgyzstan Sign Protocol on Law Enforcing Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA-ATA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Russia and Kyrgyzstan signed
a protocol on cooperation between the law-enforcing agencies of
the two countries at a three-day meeting of the interior ministers
of the Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS) held in Kyrgyzstan,
reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
Kyrgyz Interior Minister Omurbek Kutuyev told the press after
the meeting that under the document for 2000-01, Russia will help
the Kyrgyz Interior Ministry combat organized crimes,
international terrorism and drug trafficking along the Central
Asia drug-smuggling route leading to Russia.
</P>
<P>
The Russian Interior Ministry will also train special personnel
for its Kyrgyz counterpart, the protocol said.
</P>
<P>
The signing of the document indicated that Russia began to
carry out its promise made by Interior Minister Vladimir Rushailo
on August 25 in Tajikistan that Moscow would help the Central
Asian countries combat international terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The ministerial meeting, convened in Kyrgyzstan's Cholpon-Ata
resort, came amidst a spate of international terrorist incursions
into Kyrgyzstan and Uzbekistan since early August, which have
caused violent conflicts and tension in the region.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, the CIS interior ministers reached an agreement
to jointly fight against terrorism, religious extremism and drug
trafficking. 
</P>
