<HEADLINE> U.N. Security Council Urges Indonesia to Disarm Militia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Security Council on Friday urged the Government of Indonesia to
immediately disarm and disband the militiamen in West Timor of
Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
In its resolution which was unanimously adopted, the 15-member
security council also called on Indonesia to restore law and
ensure safety and security in the refugee camps and for
humanitarian workers in West Timor, and to prevent cross-border
incursions by the militia into East Timor.
</P>
<P>
A group of militiamen against the independence of East Timor on
Wednesday stormed the local office of the United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugee (UNHCR) in West Timor and killed three
UNHCR workers.
</P>
<P>
The incident forced the U.N. agency to suspend its aid
activities for an estimated 100,000 East Timorese refugees in West
Timor, who fled their homes amid chaos following the U.N.-brokered
referendum in August 1999, which turned to be in favor of East
Timor's independence.
</P>
<P>
The council stressed that those responsible for the attack on
international personnel in West and East Timor must be brought to
justice.
</P>
<P>
The council urged the Indonesian authorities to take immediate
and effective measures to ensure the safe return of refugees who
choose to go back to East Timor and stressed the need for parallel
programs to resettle individuals who choose not to return.
</P>
<P>
The council stressed that UNHCR workers cannot return to West
Timor until there is a credible security guarantee, including real
progress towards disarming and disbanding the militias.
</P>
<P>
The council underlined the United Nations Transitional
Administration in East Timor should respond robustly to the
militia threat in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
The council decided to dispatch as soon as possible a mission to
the region to discuss the implementation of this resolution.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
