<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Pakistani English Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in Pakistan's leading English newspaper on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan Observer:
</P>
<P>
-- Pakistani President Muhammad Rafiq Tarar said on Friday that
India should respond positively to Pakistan's offer of
unconditional talks on Kashmir issue to avert war threats in South
Asia.
</P>
<P>
-- Indian Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee has rejected
talks with Pakistan until it gives up, what he said, "cross-border
terrorism".
</P>
<P>
The Nation:
</P>
<P>
-- Pakistan aims to achieve an ambitious 30 billion U.S.
dollars export target by the end of the decade (year 2010) and a
new industrial policy is being chalked out to reach this mark, an
official told The Nation on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Frontier Post:
</P>
<P>
-- The Sindh High Court Chief Justice Syed Saeed Ashad on
Friday said that no one objected the October 12 take-over or
demonstrated in favor of ousted Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif, and
that fears about bloodshed, chaos etc. were nothing but an
imagination of the accused.
</P>
<P>
The News:
</P>
<P>
-- The Pakistan International Airlines (PIA) is facing a
serious cash flow problem due to rising debt burden and heavy
losses, said official sources. According to latest figures, the
total debt of PIA has increased to 33 billion rupees (589 million
dollars), while the airline incurred a loss of 1.26 billion rupees
(22.5 million dollars) during the first six months of the year
ending June 30,2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
