<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Charges Foreigners with Jeopardizing Education Pursuit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar leader Lieutenant-
General Khin Nyunt Friday charged some 15 foreigners with
jeopardizing the present peaceful pursuit of education in the
country in collusion with the opposition National League for
Democracy (NLD).
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a ceremony marking the Year 2000 International
Literacy Day, Khin Nyunt, first secretary of the Myanmar State
Peace and Development Council, accused them of holding a trumped-
up discussions on education at the party's headquarters on August
21 and having it videotaped and distributed to other countries,
official newspaper The New Light of Myanmar reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Khin Nyunt further accused the foreigners of masterminding
plans to dampen the enthusiasm and spirit of the students and the
people, and create difficulties for the country's Education for
All, continuing education, education improvement programs and its
related special four-year plan.
</P>
<P>
He warned against such flagrant interference in the internal
affairs of Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
According to a government statement released last weekend, the
Myanmar government is also investigating into a matter in
connection with these foreigners who, as well as a team from the U.
S. Congress, visited the NLD headquarters on that day.
</P>
<P>
The authorities also carried out a search operation at the
party's headquarters on September 2, the same day when some NLD
leaders, including general secretary Aung San Suu Kyi, were
brought back from Dala area in Yangon division where they had been
barred from travelling further after staying there for eight days.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, all universities in Myanmar were reopened in late
July without official announcement following a long closure since
December 1996 for students' involvement in street demonstrations
against the government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
