<HEADLINE> UNHCR Ends Operation in Guatemala </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) said on Friday that its
activities had come to an end in relation to the voluntary return
of the Guatemalans and related programs.
</P>
<P>
The UNHCR said in a communique that all its programs during the
last nine years were carried out in coordination with the
Guatemalan government and other international organizations.
</P>
<P>
During a ceremony to officially declare the end of the UNHCR
programs, a UNHCR official said several programs had been
implemented to help refugees who had returned to Guatemala. These
programs started with negotiations on a voluntary repatriation of
some 8,000 families, or 43,000 people.
</P>
<P>
During the first nine months after their return, each family
received food, agriculture implements, accommodation and medical
assistance. The UNHCR also helped Guatemala in infrastructure
development, including road building.
</P>
<P>
Tens of thousands of Guatemalans fleeing their country's civil
war started to flock into Mexico and the United States in 1981.
The war came to an end in late 1996 after the government and
rebels reached a peace agreement, leaving behind 200,000 people
being killed or missing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
