<HEADLINE> CIS States Reach Anti-Terrorism Agreement for Central Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA-ATA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The interior ministers of 11
former Soviet states Friday signed an agreement on jointly
combating terrorism, religious extremism and organized crimes in
Central Asia at the end of their three-day meeting in Kyrgyzstan.
</P>
<P>
Amid a spate of terrorist incursions into the region, the
ministers from the Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS) also
reviewed the coordination and cooperation in fighting against
terrorism among their countries, Interfax news agency quoted
Russian First Deputy Interior Minister Valery Federov as saying
after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, convened in the Cholpon-Ata resort of Kyrgyzstan,
came against the backdrop that international terrorist activities
in Chechnya have become rampant and already spilt over to Central
Asia.
</P>
<P>
Federov urged the CIS, which groups all the former Soviet
states except the three Baltic nations, to intensify their efforts
in this regard.
</P>
<P>
He said that combating across-border drug trafficking was
another topic of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Aware of the seriousness of the problem, the ministers agreed
that the CIS members should unify legislation and give traffickers
no chance, Pederov said.
</P>
<P>
Also on Friday, Kyrgyz President Askar Akayev, during a meeting
with participants of the meeting, said closer coordination among
law-enforcing agencies of the CIS countries would help in
maintaining regional peace and security.
</P>
<P>
Turkmenistan was not represented at the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
