<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Pledges Support for Stronger U.N. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Russian President
Vladimir Putin on Friday pledged his support for a stronger United
Nations based on international law, according to the U.N.
spokesmen's office.
</P>
<P>
In his meeting with U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan Friday
evening, Putin, who is here attending the three-day U.N.
Millennium Summit which just concluded, expressed his satisfaction
with the summit exercise, and in particular with roundtable
discussions among heads of state or government.
</P>
<P>
Putin and Annan agreed that the most difficult part laying
ahead is to implement the United Nations Millennium Declaration
adopted at the end of the summit.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, they discussed conflict resolution, rapid
reaction capability for peacekeepers, post-conflict reconstruction
and the U.N. reform.
</P>
<P>
Putin expressed interest in reviving the U.N. Military Staff
Committee which coordinates military activity of the five
permanent members of the Security Council in support of
international peace and security, but which has never been
effective.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, Putin said the founding principles of the U.N.
must be upheld and he emphasized the importance of member states
operating on the basis of consensus.
</P>
<P>
On Iraq, Putin told the U.N. chief that Russia has lost 30
billion U.S. dollars due to the sanctions regime against that
country.
</P>
<P>
They also discussed the on-going efforts to bring about full
compliance with the Security Council resolutions on Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
