<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Not to Extend Ceasefire Agreement in Aceh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian Defense Minister
Mahfud M.D. said the ceasefire agreement between the government
and the Free Aceh Movement (GAM) will not be extended beyond
December because it is too advantageous to the province's
separatist rebels.
</P>
<P>
The first three-month truce agreement was signed in Switzerland
on May 12 and came into effect on June 2. After it expired on
September 2, the two sides agreed to extend the so-called "
humanitarian pause" for an unspecified period.
</P>
<P>
During the implementation of ceasefire, GAM has been able to
stockpile thousands of weapons and build up its combat forces, the
minister said Friday in Surabaya, capital of East Java province.
</P>
<P>
The GAM has been launching acts of terror, such as replacing
pro-Jakarta subdistrict heads and village heads with members of
the separatist movement, the Indonesian Observer Saturday quoted
the minister as saying.
</P>
<P>
Because those actions have been taking place during the
humanitarian pause, the government has not been able to take any
action to stop the rebels, he claimed.
</P>
<P>
Despite that, he said, the government has decided to extend the
humanitarian pause until December, providing that GAM carries out
its activities as part of the Unilateral Republic of Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
In a nutshell, the government says GAM must drop its demand for
the creation of an independent state, and must accept the offer of
special autonomy.
</P>
<P>
"Anything beyond those requirements will be ignored," said the
defense minister.
</P>
<P>
Muhfud warned if GAM breaches the agreement, the government
could unilaterally cancel the ceasefire. He reiterated that
Indonesia will remain united, adding that independence calls from
Aceh and Irian Jaya will fall on deaf ears in Jakarta. "At all
costs, Aceh and Irian Jaya will remain part of Indonesia," he
stressed.
</P>
<P>
Separatist in Aceh have been fighting since 1975 for
independence in their resource-rich homeland. At least 5,000
people have been killed in the past decade.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, at least 12 people including three policemen were
killed in the past few days after the signing of the second
ceasefire accord between the two sides. 
</P>
</TEXT>
