<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Fund on Research Demanded in Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Australia risks losing its
place in the international research effort if it does not spend
more money.
</P>
<P>
According to The Australian daily Saturday, a report based on a
survey of 270 researchers said that Australia must spend at least
2.6 billion Australian dollars (1.46 billion U.S. dollars) on
research and development over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
"Most Australian researchers working overseas did want to
return to Australia to a research position," the report said,
adding that "however, considerable concern was expressed about the
availability of research funds, poor job security and lack of
career structure and opportunities in the Australian research
sector."
</P>
<P>
Rob Ramsay, president of the Australian Society for Medical
Research was quoted by the daily as saying that researchers saw
Australia in danger of being uncoupled from the rest of the
international research community and becoming nothing but a
training ground feeding researchers to overseas.
</P>
<P>
Australia has a serious brain drain problem with the United
States, Germany, France, the UK and Japan luring the brightest
from it.
</P>
<P>
Every year, about 40,000 Australians reportedly go to England
and altogether 400,000 are working there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
