<HEADLINE> Drug Traffickers Fund Colombian Rebels, Paramilitaries: U.S. Ambassador </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOGOTA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Drug traffickers in Colombia
finance both right-wing paramilitary groups and left-wing rebels,
said the U.S. Ambassador to Bogota Friday.
</P>
<P>
Ann Patterson, who assumed her post two weeks ago, made the
statement to the press after meeting with Colombian Defense
Minister Luis Fernando Ramirez, who on Tuesday triggered a
controversy by asking at a congress session when the issue of the
financing of paramilitarism would be discussed.
</P>
<P>
"That is the reason for which the United States supports the
Plan Colombia, because it has a full justification that the FARC
and other groups that are outlawed finance their illicit
activities with money they obtain from the laboratories that
produce cocaine," the ambassador told the press.
</P>
<P>
The Plan Colombia, which involves 1.3 billion U.S. dollars in
aid to Colombia, is a series of projects of President Andres
Pastrana for the war against drugs, the search for peace and
development, and the substitution of illegal cultivation.
</P>
<P>
The Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia (FARC), the largest
and oldest surviving rebel force in Latin America, has 15,000
members and controls about 40 percent of Colombia's territory.
</P>
<P>
The FARC is engaged in slow-moving peace talks with the
government, but no cease-fire deal has ever been agreed on as part
of the peace process, which aims to end a decade-old conflict in
which 35,000 people have died. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
