<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New SFOR Commander in Bosnia Takes Over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, September 8 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Lieutenant-General Michael
Dodson took over on Friday the command of the NATO-led
Stabilization Force (SFOR) in Bosnia from U.S. Lieutenant-General
Ronald Adams, becoming the fifth commander of the force.
</P>
<P>
The takeover ceremony at SFOR's main base on the outskirts of
Sarajevo was presided over by U.S. General Joseph Ralston, supreme
commander of NATO forces in Europe, Bosnian state news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Dodson, whose tenure is one year, comes from MacDill Air Force
Base, Florida, where he was serving as deputy Commander-in-Chief
and Chief of Staff, U.S. Central Command.
</P>
<P>
The 20,000-men-strong SFOR has overseen in Bosnia the military
aspects of the Dayton peace agreement that ended the 1992-95
Bosnian war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
