<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Argentine Creates Risk Fund for Small Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The first Risk Capital
Fund for Small and Medium Enterprises (Pymes) in Argentina was
created Friday by the joint contributions of the Interamerican
Development Bank (IDB), the Investments Multilateral Fund (FOMIN)
and the Credicoop Bank.
</P>
<P>
According to Credicoop president Raul Guelman, IDB Argentina
director Ricardo Carciofi and Pymes secretary Guillermo Busso, the
fund has a capital of 32 million U.S. dollars, with 12 million
dollars contributed by the IDB, FOMIN, and Credicoop, and the rest
by other investors.
</P>
<P>
The risk fund is the first of its kind set up in Argentina, but
the 23rd in the whole of Latin America. The fund will serve firms
with sales volume less than 5 million dollars a year and with less
than 100 employees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
