<HEADLINE> Bush Agrees to Negotiate on Debates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 8 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Republican
presidential candidate George W. Bush Friday agreed to negotiate
on presidential debates to end the dispute with his Democratic
rival Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
Texas Governor Bush directed his campaign chairman Don Evans to
inform the Commission on Presidential Debates that he would meet
with the commission and the Gore campaign to work out a plan for
debates, according to his spokesman Karen Hughes.
</P>
<P>
The Bush and Gore campaigns are expected to meet with the
presidential debate commission next week to negotiate terms for a
series of televised debates between the two presidential
contenders.
</P>
<P>
"The Bush campaign has accepted the Commission on Presidential
Debates' invitation to meet. We are working to schedule a meeting
with Bush and Gore campaign representatives next week," said
commission executive director Janet Brown.
</P>
<P>
Bush earlier insisted that he would only attend one formal
debate sponsored by the commission, and accept two other less-
formal TV appearances instead of the formal ones.
</P>
<P>
Bush had proposed to attend a TV appearance in an NBC program
on Tuesday night even if Gore refused to show up, but NBC informed
the Bush campaign that there would be no debate as scheduled
unless both candidates agreed to appear.
</P>
<P>
Bush received harsh criticism from several major newspapers for
refusing to attend the formal debates to be arranged by the
bipartisan debate commission.
</P>
<P>
Vice President Al Gore said that he would consider other
formats only after Bush agreed to the three formal debates
sponsored by the commission.
</P>
<P>
"We are pleased that the Bush campaign has agreed to meet with
the bipartisan commission on presidential debates. We look forward
to that meeting," said William Daley, Gore's campaign chairman.
</P>
</TEXT>
