<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Australian Currency Gets into Trouble </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar dropped
to 55.89 U.S. cents Friday at the close of the Sydney trading, the
lowest level since 1998, despite the fact that the Reserve Bank
intervened for the third successive day.
</P>
<P>
The Australian currency was floated in December 1983. Since
then, only for one time it had been under 57 U.S. cents, and
affected by the Asian economic crisis, had a brief touch on the 55.
30 mark in August 1998.
</P>
<P>
The current round of steep fall of the dollar started from
November 1999. The Asian economies regained their vigor while
Australia entered its ninth continuing year of high growth.
</P>
<P>
As Prime Minister John Howard said happily "the Australian
economy at the present time is stronger than it's been for more
than 30 years." And economists foretold the Australian dollar
would soar towards the brilliant mark of 80 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
Thus nobody noticed the snakes in the grass, though they had
been there for a long time.
</P>
<P>
Australian officials explained that all the troubles came from
a too strong U.S. dollar and for the country's lack of
participation in the information technology revolution.
</P>
<P>
In the field of research and development, Australia is weak and
seems getting weaker. Universities and researching institutes are
puzzled by the lack of fund and forced to make money themselves.
Young and ambitious researchers and professionals leave for abroad.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the Australians have been content with using
computers and getting profits from doing so rather than making
them. There is no one big IT enterprise in the country with stocks
above 10 Australian dollars. As a result, capital is sucked out
along with brains.
</P>
<P>
However, there is not only one snake. There is another one:
high foreign debt.
</P>
<P>
Australia is ranked 28th in the world in national savings, an
incredible 43rd on financial risk and 28th on financial debt.
Given its huge debt and current account deficit, the country must
borrow big sums every day. Latest official figures show that 36
billion Australian dollars (about 20.16 billion U.S. dollars) was
added to its debt in the year to June as the banks borrowed
heavily on global markets.
</P>
<P>
Now, the country's total liabilities, including foreign
ownership, have soared to 404 billion Australian dollars (226.24
billion U.S. dollars) or 64 percent of GDP compared to 45 percent
10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
All these have made international investors nervous and quick
to sell the Australian dollar in big quantities. The trouble with
Australian dollar has once again exposed the snakes in the grass
of the continent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
