<HEADLINE> Canada, Argentina Sign Environment, Energy Agreements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Canada and Argentina signed two
agreements here Friday on cooperation in environment protection
and in the development of atomic energy.
</P>
<P>
Attending the signing of the two documents were Canadian
Foreign Minister Lloyd Axworthy, Industry Minister John Manley,
Environment Minister David Anderson and Adalberto Rodriguez
Giavarini, Argentinean Minister of Foreign Relations,
International Trade and Worship.
</P>
<P>
The agreements were signed during the two-day official working
visit by Argentinean President Fernando de la Rua, who arrived
here earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
"Canada and Argentina have significantly enhanced their
bilateral co-operation over the past decade," said Axworthy. "
Today's agreements will contribute to a cleaner global environment
and help to reduce the amount of waste produced by nuclear power
plants," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Memorandum of Understanding on Environmental Co-operation
will facilitate the transfer of clean technologies.
</P>
<P>
"I'm pleased that a number of Canadian environmental firms have
formed partnerships and won contracts as a direct result of their
participation in Canada's activities in Argentina," said Manley.
</P>
<P>
Under the Joint Study Program Agreement, the Atomic Energy of
Canada Limited and Nucleoelectrica Argentina S.A. propose to
undertake a joint feasibility study on using slightly enriched
uranium in the CANDU reactor at Embalse, Argentina.
</P>
<P>
The conversion of a nuclear reactor from natural uranium to
SEU can result in fuel savings of over 25 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
