personal physiotherapist and will return to action in Japan on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Frye said:"If he runs under 13.30 seconds in Tokyo then look
for a big one from Allen in Sydney. I am sure it is going to be a
great race in Sydney. I know Mr. Jackson is starting to run into
form and I know Allen will be on top form."
</P>
<P>
"He was more injured than we thought but things are going very
well for Allen now. He has put some really good training in," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Jackson, who regained his world 110m title in Seville last
year after defending champion Johnson pulled out before his semi-
final through injury, has also been battling with problems.
</P>
<P>
But Jackson's own coach Malcolm Arnold believes that the 33-
year-old Welshman will be at his best in Sydney and ready to seize
the only title missing from his trophy cabinet at the fourth
attempt.
</P>
<P>
"Colin is running very well. He is fine, in good shape," said
Arnold. "It is shame he couldn't have had a few more races, but
there was nothing we could do about that."
</P>
<P>
"We have still got another two weeks before he goes to Sydney
so we are just putting the icing on the cake really," he added.
</P>
