<HEADLINE> Ottey to Run a Record Sixth Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SYDNEY, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Merlene Ottey, the favorite
daughter of Jamaica, was on her way for a record sixth Olympics
against a dire fact that the 40-year-old was still crying for her
first ever Olympic gold medal.
</P>
<P>
Ottey, who returned to competition in July after a 12-month
drugs ban was overturned, has made it plain she expects to run
track and field's blue riband event plus the 100m relay in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
However, the Jamaica's athletes selectors were still short of
final decisions on her outings in both events, as team manager
Winston Ulett said that "we saw that and we heard that but we
don't know anything about it."
</P>
<P>
The sprint queen flew into Australia on Wednesday, and was
staying somewhere in Brisbane where the rest of the Jamaican team
is preparing for the Games.
</P>
<P>
Ulett said Ottey would run the relay if she continued the form
shown since the Jamaican trials in July but on decision on whether
she would line up in the 100m would be made until September 19,
the day before nominations are due.
</P>
<P>
He said Ottey would be vying for the three individual spots
with the trio of women who finished ahead of her at the trials in
July.
</P>
<P>
Ottey ran 11.27 seconds in the trials and Ulett noted she had
twice run faster and twice slower since then.
</P>
<P>
Ottey has won seven Olympic medals, but none of them gold, and
14 world championship medals including six golds, which is more
than any other athlete.
</P>
<P>
The Jamaica's woman sprinter was banned after testing positive
to the anabolic steroid nandralone in July 1999 but the suspension
was lifted in July this year by an International Amateur Athletic
Federation panel.
</P>
<P>
Tested about 100 times since 1979, Ottey dismissed the initial
finding as a "terrible mistake" and the Jamaican Amateur Athletics
Federation in November last year found her not guilty of the
allegations.
</P>
<P>
She was designated a roving ambassador for Jamaica in 1993.
</P>
