<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Develops Software Simulating Oil Exploitation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 9 (Xinhua) -- China has developed a new kind
of software capable of simulating the change of oil-bearing
formations in exploited oil fields, thus helping oil companies get
information about the remaining oil and a cost-effective way of
getting it.
</P>
<P>
 Feng Yulin, director of the Institute of Software under the
Chinese Academy of Sciences, said Friday that the software, known
as high-performance numerical parallel software for simulating oil
reserve, or PRIS 2.0, is the result of a 10-year research effort
by the institute.
</P>
<P>
 Application of the software in China's state-of-the-art
computers, such as Shengwei (Invincible Might) and Downing
computers in the past year, has enabled researchers and their oil
company partners to simulate the change in oil-bearing formations
from when the oil fields were first put in place to pump out oil,
said the director.
</P>
<P>
Then they can get the information on the remaining oil, which
is vital for choosing the most effective technique, said Feng.
</P>
<P>
Experts say the software is very important for China's oil
industry as most of the oil output comes from the oil fields that
have been used for almost 30 years, including Daqing Oil Field in
northeast China, the leading oil field in the country.
</P>
<P>
The software will eventually help oil companies produce oil
from those fields in an efficient way to power the country's
growing economy.
</P>
<P>
The software has passed the test by American multinational
company James Atlas SSI, which describes it as reliable and
effective.
</P>
<P>
According to experts with the institute, the PRIS 2.0 is as
good as the imported software used by Chinese oil companies at the
moment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
