<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Students in Sanctions-Stricken Iraq Start New School Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Students across the sanctions-
stricken Iraq started their new school year on Saturday, faced with
lack of fund, equipment, textbooks and even teachers.
</P>
<P>
The pupils at Al-Razi elementary school in the center of capital
Baghdad held a flag-raising ceremony, chanting the Iraqi national
anthem and pledged loyalty to President Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
But they have to bear the bite of the sweeping sanctions,
imposed by the United Nations for Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in
1990. The school has no new equipment and no fund. In the
classrooms, two pupils have to share a desk designed for one; at
least half of the textbooks are old ones.
</P>
<P>
Before the sanctions, all the children received a simple but
nutritious meal of milk, biscuits, and fresh fruit each day, but
now schools are neither able to renew their physical infrastructure
nor to invest in students' health well-being.
</P>
<P>
To most of the students, computer is something they can only
dream of.
</P>
<P>
Education in Iraq now remains free, but parents of the students
are encouraged to donate a few U.S. dollars to the schools where
their children attend. But even a few dollars are a small fortune
to ordinary Iraqis.
</P>
<P>
A teacher's monthly salary could be as much as 500 dollars
before the sanctions, now a teacher is lucky to get an average of
6,000 dinars (three dollars) a month. To make ends meet, most
teachers have to take second or even third jobs.
</P>
<P>
In Iraq, it is no news that a school teacher has to sell
cigarettes, ice cream or drive taxis to make more money. Neither is
it a surprise that every year more than 100,000 children drop out
of school to help support their families.
</P>
<P>
However, things were totally different before the sanctions.
According to the U.N. Development Program's 1991 human development
report, Iraq's combined primary and secondary enrollment ratio for
1989 stood at 75 percent, higher than the 70 percent for all
developing countries.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Children's Funds (UNICEF) has estimated that no more
than 45 percent of Iraq's schools have even the basic
infrastructure needed for teaching to take place. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
