<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Government Urged to Attract More Foreign Investments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 9 (Xinhua) -- A senior Iranian official here
on Saturday urged more government efforts to address the country's
shortage of foreign investments.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, Iran attracted less than 1 billion U.S. dollars in
foreign investments, which is indicative of the slow pace in
mobilizing resources to attract foreign capital, said Mohammad
Jafar Eslami, deputy minister of mines and metals for planning,
development and renovation.
</P>
<P>
Given the total direct foreign investments of 872 billion
dollars in the world in 1999, Iran, with 1 percent of the world
population, should have absorbed about 8.7 billion dollars of the
total, he said, quoted by the official Islamic Republic News
Agency.
</P>
<P>
Eslami urged the government to make more efforts to speed up the
pace in attracting foreign investments. Security, foreign policy
and publicity are among the factors that prepare the ground for
foreign investments, he stated.
</P>
<P>
The official noted that the Ministry of Mines and Metals had
offered 100 projects worth 10 billion dollars, adding that with the
right and more transparent investment environment, the amount of
foreign investments in this sector will rise.
</P>
<P>
He said that a measure has been adopted to prolong the
excavation period of the country's mines from five to 25 years.
This is expected to be an incentive for potential investors in the
sector, he said.
</P>
<P>
Promoting incentives for investments is a feature of the third
five-year economic development plan (March 2000-March 2005)
compared to that of the first and second development plans, he
pointed out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
