<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The Saudi-based telecommunications group Silki La
Silki (SLS) has signed a deal with Landis and Gyr of Switzerland,
for the development and manufacture of payphones working on the
Thuraya Satellite Telecommunications Company's network.
</P>
<P>
The deal, signed at SLS's headquarters in Riyadh, is designed to
develop, supply and install pre-paid chip card based satellite
payphones in Thuraya's coverage area, which includes 99 markets in
Europe, Africa and Asia, the official WAM news agency of the United
Arab Emirates reported on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Under the deal, the satellite payphone service will be
operational in the year 2001.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, SLS entered into a commercial partnership with Thuraya,
by which it has become the service provider for Thuraya's satellite
enhanced payphone service.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran and Russia have agreed to set up a liquefaction
plant in Iran to produce liquefied hydrogen.
</P>
<P>
The plant, to be built soon, is part of the country's plan to
replace fossil fuels with new environment-friendly energy sources,
said Faramarz Golshani, managing-director of the New Energies
Organization.
</P>
<P>
He said the liquefied hydrogen is used as fuel for diesel
engines of heavy-duty vehicles.
</P>
<P>
The official added that Iran has launched a four-year study on
replacing fossil energies with new energies as well as setting up
solar energy plants and wind power farms.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Over 70 Taiwanese exhibitors, including several
internationally recognized manufacturers, will display a wide range
of IT products at Gitex 2000, to be held at the Dubai World Trade
Center (DWTC) on October 28-November 1.
</P>
<P>
China's Taiwan province, which is the third largest IT products
suppliers in the world, following the U.S. and Japan, produced IT
products worth 47 billion U.S. dollars in 1999, according to a
press release from the DWTC on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The General Postal Authority (GPA) of the United
Arab Emirates (UAE) has registered an increase in mail parcels
during the first half of 2000.
</P>
<P>
GPA Director General Abdullah Ibrahim Al Daboos said that the
number of outgoing parcels in the first half of the year increased
by 37 percent, compared to the same period in 1999.
</P>
<P>
He said that faster delivery and higher standard of services are
the main reason for the growth. 
</P>
