<DOCNO> XIE20000909.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian PM Says Industrial Countries Responsible for High Oil Price </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Italian Prime Minister Giuliano
Amato Saturday warned that the industrial countries brought the
present oil price on themselves.
</P>
<P>
Pledging to bring Italian petrol prices within the EU average,
he told reporters that the industrial countries had been
irresponsible towards the oil producers by when they watched the
price of oil drop to 10 U.S. dollars a barrel -- "and no one did
anything."
</P>
<P>
"We complain, but we forget what we did to them," he said, "
these are developing countries whose revenue comes from oil. No
one offered a helping hand, so they did their own thing and cut
back production."
</P>
<P>
Amato, who also said he is sure an equilibrium point will be
found in the oil market, confirmed that the government's plans to
reduce Italian petrol prices by maintaining the present 50-lire
tax discount and rationalizing the distribution system to reduce
costs.
</P>
<P>
Similar policies are being urged by the EU, especially
increased competition among the oil companies to bring down prices.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the EU's finance and economics ministers Saturday
called on the Opec oil producers to increase their production
enough to bring oil prices down to about 28 dollars a barrel.
</P>
<P>
The final statement at their meeting in France described high
oil prices as a "source of great concern" and said they should
return to the levels which favor world growth.
</P>
<P>
The high prices ruling for most of this year, now as high as 34-
35 dollars a barrel, have blighted growth prospects in the EU and
elsewhere and, by threatening European prospects, have also sent
the euro plunging to record lows against the dollar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
