<HEADLINE> Protests Trigger First Fuel Shortages in Britain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Fuel shortages were taking hold
at some petrol stations as oil refinery blockades in England and
Wales start to bite on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Shell, BP and Sainsbury's and Tesco supermarkets have all
reported supply problems as protesters vent their anger at rising
fuel prices.
</P>
<P>
But retailers have sought to calm the situation amid reports
of panic buying, saying a fuel crisis is unlikely. The blockades
came as Europe's finance ministers appealed to the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) to reduce prices ahead of
their meeting in Vienna on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The biggest protest over rising fuel price in Britain has been
at Milford Haven, Pembrokeshire, where two oil refineries run by
Texaco and Elf have been blocked by around 50 lorries since Friday.
</P>
<P>
Workers on Saturday morning were forced to enter the depot on
foot as protesters including members of the public, farmers, taxi
drivers and coach operators blocked road access.
</P>
<P>
Shell Oil's Stanlow refinery at Ellesmere Port, in Cheshire,
and a petrol distribution depot at Avonmouth near Bristol are also
being targeted.
</P>
<P>
Shell warned that 20 to 30 stations in the North West would
run out of petrol "imminently" as a result of the Stanlow protests,
while Sainsbury's said two of its 223 petrol stations had already
run out of fuel.
</P>
<P>
But Ray Holloway, director of the Petrol Retailers'
Association, said that 30 or so filling stations out of 1,200 in
the region did not mean Britain was running out of petrol.
</P>
<P>
The protests could be spreading to Ireland next week after the
Irish Road Haulage Association, which represents 1,200 of Ireland'
s 4,000 truckers, announced protests on Friday and the following
Monday in support of its claim for a reduction in fuel duty.
</P>
</TEXT>
