<HEADLINE> Italian GP: Schumacher Wins Pole Position </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Ferrari's Michael Schumacher was
poised to strike back at championship leader Mika Hakkinen
Saturday after winning pole position in the starting grid for
tomorrow's Italian Grand Prix.
</P>
<P>
Beside him on the grid will be Ferrari team-mate, Rubens
Barrichello, who also clocked a faster time than Hakkinen. The
Finn will start third, with McLaren's other driver, David
Coulthard, back in seventh.
</P>
<P>
Schumacher led the Formula 1 drivers' championship until two
races ago when Hakkinen overtook him. Then, two weeks ago in
Belgium, Hakkinen's McLaren shot past Schumacher's Ferrari when
the German was within four laps of victory.
</P>
<P>
After winning four races in the early part of the Formula 1
championship, the German has disappointed fans in recent Grand
Prix races and raised fears that he will fail for the third year
running to deliver the championship title he has promised Ferrari.
</P>
<P>
Now six points separate the rivals at the top of the driver's
standings. With four races to go and 40 points up for grabs, the
stage is set for a dramatic finish to the Formula 1 season.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, Schumacher said he was confident he could
still win the title that has eluded Ferrari for 20 years.
</P>
<P>
He also promised significant changes to his car, which has been
visibly slower than the two McLarens in recent races.
</P>
<P>
Today's first and second place on the grid was Ferrari's first
since the Malaysian Grand Prix eleven months ago.
</P>
<P>
In that race Schumacher led till just before the end when he
allowed then team-mate Eddie Irvine to pass him. 
</P>
</TEXT>
