<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuelan President Forecasts Oil Prices Drop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Venezuelan President Hugo
Chavez was quoted as saying that key oil producers including his
country were making effort to help bring crude oil prices down to
25-28 U.S. dollars a barrel.
</P>
<P>
Venezuela, the largest oil exporter in the Western Hemisphere,
is due to host the second Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries (OPEC) summit later this month.
</P>
<P>
He told the Brazilian news agency Estado de Sao Paulo that
Brazilian President Fernando Henrique Cardoso "need not worry
because Venezuela is working and is going to succeed in
stabilizing the price of this commodity."
</P>
<P>
High fuel costs have sparked concern and even outrage in
several consuming nations.
</P>
<P>
As international pressure mounts on OPEC to pump more oil to
stem surging fuel prices, OPEC members said Saturday they
supported raising their official output by at least half a million
barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
OPEC members agreed in June to pump an additional 500,000
barrels a day if the average price for several types of OPEC crude
exceeded 28 dollars for 20 consecutive business days.
</P>
<P>
As of Thursday, this average OPEC price was 33.84 dollars and
had been higher than  28 dollars a barrel for 19 consecutive days.
Prices surged to 10-year highs in New York and London this week,
surpassing 34 dollars a barrel.
</P>
<P>
With the production of some 3 million barrels per day (bpd),
Venezuela is currently exporting more than 1.8 million bpd.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
